              margin-top: 2px !important;">Japanese elderly women prefer jail over freedom</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4"><a href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-25-01-2025-r2-3-tochigi-womens-prison" target="_blank">Tochigi Women's Prison</a> in Japan is a strange anomaly. Elderly inmates prefer to stay in prison or commit repeated crimes to stay there. This raises critical questions about the country's aging population and loneliness. If they choose freedom, the inmates must struggle for meals, healthcare, and eldercare. Some older prisoners say that life feels more stable than outside existence.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">Many have families who have abandoned these elderly women. Aged inmates often struggle with reintegration due to a lack of family support. Japan is addressing this with guidance on independent living, substance addiction recovery, and how to navigate family relationships, but the challenges of eldercare persist both in and out of prison.</p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-divider border-width="1px" border-style="solid" border-color="lightgrey" padding="0px 12px" />
