          <h2 style="              
              font-size: 20px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 500;
              margin-top: 2px !important;">Trudeau warns Trump of robust response if he imposes unfair tariffs</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">Prime Minister Justin Trudeau warned that Canada would respond with "robust, rapid" retaliatory measures if President Donald Trump imposes tariffs in February. Trudeau claimed <a href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-25-01-2025-r3-4-dollar-for-dollar" target="_blank">dollar-for-dollar</a> tariffs on U.S. goods, particularly oil, steel, and aluminum. While the primary goal is to avoid trade conflict, his warning shows Canada is ready to deploy whatever measures are necessary to try and force Trump to reverse course.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">Trudeau warned that consumers would bear the costs if Canada entered a trade war to stop Trump. Meanwhile, Trump claims the tariffs are necessary to address drug and migrant issues despite low border seizures. Alberta Premier Danielle Smith advocates for a diplomatic resolution rather than trade retaliation.</p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-divider border-width="1px" border-style="solid" border-color="lightgrey" padding="0px 12px" />
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>
