              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">Can Trump make all of his executive actions happen?</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">Not all of President Trump's executive orders (or any president's) can be implemented without legal or practical constraints. Executive orders cannot override laws passed by Congress or violate the Constitution. They are meant to direct the executive branch's operations but cannot legislate.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">Executive orders let presidents implement policies quickly, but courts and Congress can challenge them. For example, <a href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-25-01-2025-bo1-7-removing-birthright-citizenship" target="_blank">removing birthright citizenship</a> would violate the 14th Amendment, and one judge has already blocked that order. However, he can send some of these that he can’t implement automatically through the judicial and legislative branches, which in theory could happen, as the Supreme Court and Congress have a Republican majority.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">Another order that Trump would have difficulty with is renaming the Gulf of Mexico the Gulf of America. He would have to get the Geographic Names Information System to update it; while he can likely get them to agree, the <a href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-25-01-2025-bo1-8-rest-of-the-world" target="_blank">rest of the world</a> doesn’t have to follow suit.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
